    "text": "No need to skip — work around the calves instead. Sore calves the day after a run, the kind that ache when you poke or stretch them, is ordinary muscle soreness, and your data says your body handled the session well: recovery is 72, HRV at 53 ms is right on your 30-day average of 52.0 ms, resting heart rate of 58 bpm is under your usual 59.9, and you slept 8.0 h. Feeling beat plus good numbers usually just means local muscle fatigue, not systemic overload. So train today, but pick something calf-light — upper body, core, or an easy spin — and let the running muscles bounce back for a day or two. One boundary: soreness that's sharp, one-sided, swollen, or getting worse rather than better isn't normal soreness and would be worth getting looked at.",
